WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.000
 Welcome to C Programming for Everybody. My name is Charles Severance. This is my reading of the 1978 C Programming book written by Brian Kernigan and Dennis Ritchie. At times, I add my own interpretation of the material from a historical perspective.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
 Chapter 5, Pointers and Arrays

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:29.000
 Before we start Chapter 5, a quick note from your narrator. From time to time, I have been adding some of my interpretation to this book.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:40.000
 But I won't be adding anything to this chapter. I think that sections 5.1 through 5.6 contain some of the most elegantly written text in the book.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:47.000
 The concepts are clearly stated, and the example code is short, direct, and easy to understand.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:01:00.000
 Pointers are the essential difference between C and any other modern programming language, so pay close attention to this chapter and make sure that you understand it before continuing.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:13.000
 This chapter is as strong now as it was in 1978, and so without further ado, we read and listen as Kernigan and Ritchie teach us about pointers and arrays.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:25.000
 A pointer is a variable that contains the address of another variable. Pointers are very much used in C, partly because they are sometimes the only way to express a computation,

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:33.000
 and partly because they usually lead to more compact and efficient code than can be obtained in other ways.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:43.000
 Pointers have been lumped with a go-to statement as a marvelous way to create impossible-to-understand programs. This is certainly true when they are used carelessly,

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:54.000
 and it is easy to create pointers that point somewhere unexpected. With discipline, however, pointers can also be used to achieve clarity and simplicity.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.000
 This is the aspect that we will try to illustrate.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:05.000
 Section 5.1 - Pointers and Addresses

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:13.000
 Since a pointer contains the address of an object, it is possible to access the object indirectly through the pointer.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:23.000
 Suppose that x is a variable, say int, and that px is a pointer, created in some as-yet unspecified way.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:37.000
 The unary operator ampersand gives the address of an object, so the statement px = ampersand x; assigns the address of x to the variable px.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:46.000
 px is now said to point to x. The ampersand operator can be applied only to variables and array elements.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:58.000
 Constructs like ampersand (x + 1) and ampersand (3) are illegal. It is also illegal to take the address of a register variable.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:08.000
 The unary operator asterisk treats its operand as the address of the ultimate target, and accesses that address to fetch the contents.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:22.000
 Thus, if y is also an int, y = *px; assigns to y the contents of whatever px points to.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:36.000
 So the sequence px = ampersand x; y = *px; assigns the same value to y as does y = x.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
 It is also necessary to declare the variables that participate in all of this.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:04:10.000
 int x, y; int *px; The declaration of x and y is what we have seen all along. The declaration of the pointer px is new. int *px; is intended as a mnemonic.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:22.000
 It is equivalent to a variable of type int. In effect, the syntax of the declaration for a variable mimics the syntax of expressions in which the variable might appear.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:27.000
 This reasoning is useful in all cases involving complicated declarations.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:44.000
 For example, double a to f open parenthesis close parenthesis comma star dp semicolon says that in a particular expression a to f open parenthesis close parenthesis and star dp have values of type double.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:53.000
 You should also note the implication in the direction declaration that a pointer is constrained to point to a particular kind of objects.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:05.000
 Pointers can occur in expressions. For example, if px points to the integer x, then *px can occur in any context where x could.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:24.000
 y = *px + 1 sets y to 1 more than x. print f open parenthesis double quote percent d backslash n double quote comma *px close parenthesis prints the current value of x.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:41.000
 And d = square root open parenthesis open parenthesis double close parenthesis *px close parenthesis produces in d the square root of x, which is coerced into a double before being passed to square root.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:59.000
 In expressions like y = *px + 1, the unary operators * and ampersand bind more tightly than arithmetic operators, so this expression takes whatever px points at, adds 1, and assigns it to y.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:08.000
 We will return shortly to what y = *open parenthesis px + 1 close parenthesis might mean.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:29.000
 Pointer references can also occur on the left side of assignments. If px points to x, then *px = 0 sets x to 0 and *px + = 1 increments it, as does *px + +.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:46.000
 The parentheses are necessary in this last example. Without them, the expression would increment px instead of what it points to, because unary operators like * and ++ are evaluated right to left.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:07:07.000
 Finally, since pointers are variables, they can be manipulated as other variables can. If py is another pointer to int, then py = px copies the contents of px into py, thus making py point to whatever px points to.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:24.000
 Section 5.2 Pointers and Function Arguments Since C passes arguments to functions by callByValue, there is no direct way for the called function to alter the variable in the calling function.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:29.000
 What do you do if you really have to change an ordinary argument?

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:54.000
 For example, a sorting routine might exchange two out-of-order elements with a function called swap(). It's not enough to write swap(a,b); where the swap function is defined as (sample source code on page 91 of the textbook, and you can see it at www.cc4e.com/code).

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:59.000
 This is a wrong swap, by the way. This is showing you the code that you're not supposed to do.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:25.000
 Because of callByValue, swap can't affect the arguments a and b in the routine that called it.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:35.000
 Fortunately, there is a way to obtain the desired effect. The calling point program passes pointers to the values to be changed.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:57.000
 The call is swap(&a,&b;). Since the operator & gives the address of a variable, &a is a pointer to a. In swap itself, the arguments are declared to be pointers, and the actual operands are accessed through them.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:12.000
 So the correct code is on page 92.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:41.000
 One common use of pointer arguments is in functions that must return more than a single value. You might say that swap actually returns two values, the new values of its arguments.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:58.000
 As an example, consider a function getInt() which performs a free-format input conversion by breaking a stream of characters into integer values, one integer per call. getInt() has to return the value that it found, or an end-of-file signal when there is no more input.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:09.000
 These values have to be returned as separate objects, for no matter what value is used for EOF, that could also be a value of the integer.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:24.000
 One solution, which is based on the input function scanf() that we will describe in Chapter 7, is to have getInt() return EOF as its function value it finds end-of-file, and any other returned value signals a normal integer.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:38.000
 The numeric value of the integer it found is returned through an argument, which then must be a pointer to an integer. This organization separates the end-of-file status from the returned numeric value.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:49.000
 The following loop fills an array with integers by calls to getInt. int,n,array(size, semicolon)

00:10:49.000 --> 00:11:09.000
 For n=0, n less than size, double ampersand, getInt("Ampersand v, not equal EOF, semicolon n++", array sub n=v)

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:20.000
 Each call sets v to the next integer found in the input. Notice that it is essential to write ampersand v instead of v as the argument to getInt.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:28.000
 Using plain v is likely to cause an addressing error, since getInt() believes that it has been handed a valid pointer.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:44.000
 getInt() is an obvious modification to A to I, which we wrote earlier. The sample code is on page 93 of the textbook, and you can see this sample code at www.cc4e.com/code

00:11:44.000 --> 00:12:01.000
 Pound include stdio.h, getInt("pn", int*pn, semicolon), open curly brace, int c,sign

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:22.000
 While open paren, open paren, c=getCh, open paren, close paren, close paren, double equals, quote, space, quote, or c, double equals, quote, backslash, n, quote, or c, double equals, backslash, t, quote, close paren, semicolon

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.000
 This loop we've done before, and it skips the white space.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:48.000
 Sign equals one, semicolon. If open paren, c, double equals, quote, plus, quote, or c, double equals, quote, minus, quote, close paren, open curly brace, sign equals, open paren, c, double equals, quote, plus, quote, close paren, question mark, one, colon, minus one, semicolon

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:59.000
 c=getCh, to advance the character, semicolon, and then close curly brace. Those four lines record the sign.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:16.000
 Now, for *pn=0, c>=, quote, zero, quote, and c<=, quote, nine, quote, colon, semicolon, c=getCh, open paren, close paren, close curly brace

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:25.000
