00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:45.000
 If open paren, c, not equal to eof, close paren, ungetCh, open paren, c, close paren, semicolon, return c

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:56.000
 Throughout getInt, *pn is used as an ordinary int variable. We have also used getCh and ungetCh as described in Chapter 4,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:01.000
 so the one extra character that must be read can be pushed back onto the input.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:13.000
 Section 5.3, Pointers and Arrays. In C, there is a strong relationship between pointers and arrays, strong enough that pointers and arrays should really be treated simultaneously.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:20.000
 Any operation which can be achieved by array subscripting can also be done with pointers.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:28.000
 The pointer version will in general be faster, but at least to the uninitiated, somewhat harder to grasp immediately.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:44.000
 The declaration int a sub 10 defines an array a of size 10 that is a block of 10 consecutive objects named a sub 0, a sub 1, dot dot dot, a sub 9.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:50.000
 The notation a sub i means the element of the array i positions from the beginning.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:15:14.000
 If pa is a pointer to an integer declared as int *pa, then the assignment pa equals ampersand a sub 0 sets pa to point to the 0th element of a.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:19.000
 That is, pa contains the address of a sub 0.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:28.000
 Now, the assignment x equals star pa will copy the contents of a sub 0 into x.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:38.000
 If pa points to a particular element of array a, then by definition pa points to the next element.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:52.000
 If pa points to a particular element of an array a, then by definition pa plus 1 points to the next element.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:16:16.000
 And in general, pa minus i points to i elements before pa and pa plus i points to i elements after. Thus, if pa points to a sub 0, star parenthesis pa plus 1 close parenthesis refers to the contents of a sub 1.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:33.000
 pa plus i is the address of a sub i and star print and star open print pa plus i is the contents of a sub i.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:38.000
 These remarks are true regardless of the type of the variables in the array a.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:51.000
 The definition of adding 1 to a pointer and by extension all pointer arithmetic is that the increment is scaled by the size of the storage of the object that is pointed to.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:17:01.000
 Thus, in pa plus i, i is multiplied by the size of the objects that pa points to before being added to pa.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:07.000
 The correspondence between indexing and pointer arithmetic is evidently very close.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:14.000
 In fact, a reference to an array is converted by the compiler to a pointer to the beginning of the array.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:19.000
 The effect is that the array name is a pointer expression.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:41.000
 This has quite a few useful implications. Since the name of an array is a synonym for the location of the zeroth element, the assignment pa equals ampersand a sub 0 can also be written as pa equals a.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:53.000
 Rather more surprising, at least at first sight, is the fact that a reference to a sub i can also be written as star open print a plus i closed print.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:01.000
 In evaluating a sub i, C converts it to star open print a plus i closed print immediately.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.000
 The two forms are completely equivalent.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:13.000
 Applying the operator ampersand to both parts of this equivalence, it follows that ampersand a sub i and a plus i are also identical.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:18.000
 a plus i is the address of the i-th element beyond a.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:25.000
 As on the other side of this coin, if pa is a pointer, expressions may use it with a subscript.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:33.000
 pa sub i is identical to star open print pa plus i closed print.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:44.000
 In short, any array and index expression can be rewritten as a pointer and an offset and vice versa, even in the same statement.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:49.000
 There is one difference between an array name and a pointer that must be kept in mind.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:19:03.000
 A pointer is a variable, so pa equals a and pa plus plus are sensible operations, but an array name is a constant, not a variable.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:12.000
 Constructions like a equals pa or a plus plus or p equals ampersand a are illegal.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:19.000
 When an array name is passed to a function, what is passed is the location of the beginning of the array.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:25.000
 Within the called function, this argument is a variable, just like any other variable.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:32.000
 And so an array name argument is truly a pointer that is a variable containing an address.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:39.000
 We can use this fact to write a new version of sterlin, which computes the length of the string.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:47.000
 The sample code is on page 95 of the book, and you can see it in www.cc4e.com/code.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:20:12.000
 page 95 int sterlin open paren s close paren char star s semicolon open curly brace int n semicolon 4 open parenthesis n equals 0 semicolon star s not equal quote backslash zero quote semicolon

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:24.000
 s plus plus close paren n plus plus return open paren n close paren semicolon close curly brace.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:30.000
 Incrementing s is perfectly legal, since it's a pointer variable.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:40.000
 s plus plus has no effect on the character string function that called sterlin, but merely increments the sterlin's private copy of the address.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:55.000
 As the formal parameters in a function definition, char s open square bracket close square bracket semicolon and char star s semicolon are exactly equivalent.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:01.000
 Which one should be written is determined largely by how expressions will be written in the function.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:10.000
 When an array name is passed to a function, the function can, at its convenience, believe that it has been handed either an array or a pointer and manipulated accordingly.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:17.000
 It can even use both kinds of operations if it seems appropriate and clear.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:26.000
 It is possible to pass part of an array to a function by passing a pointer to the beginning of the subarray.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:44.000
 For example, if a is an array, f open paren ampersand a sub 2 close paren and f open paren a plus 2 close paren both pass to the function f, the address of the element a sub 2.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:54.000
 Because ampersand a sub 2 and a plus 2 are both pointer expressions that refer to the third element of a.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:22:18.000
 Within f, the argument declaration can read f open paren array close paren int array open bracket close bracket semicolon dot dot dot or f open paren array close paren int star array semicolon dot dot dot.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:28.000
 So far as f is concerned, the fact that the argument really refers to a part of a larger array is really of no consequence.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:48.000
 Section 5.4 address arithmetic. If p is a pointer, then p plus plus increments p to point to the next element of whatever kind of object p points to and p plus equals i increments p to the point i elements beyond where it currently does.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:55.000
 These and similar constructions are the simplest and most common forms of pointer or address arithmetic.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:23:00.000
 C is consistent and regular in its approach to address arithmetic.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:07.000
 Its integration of pointers arrays and address arithmetic is one of the major strengths of the language.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:15.000
 Let us illustrate some of the properties by writing a rudimentary storage allocator, but useful in spite of its simplicity.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:27.000
 There are two routines Alec open paren and close paren returns a pointer p to end consecutive character positions, which can be used by the caller of Alec for storing characters.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:34.000
 Free open paren p close paren releases the storage thus acquired so it can later be reused.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:42.000
 These routines are rudimentary because the calls to free must be made in the opposite order to the calls on Alec.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:48.000
 That is, storage managed by Alec and free is a stack or last in first out.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:56.000
 The standard seed library provides analogous functions which have no such restrictions and in Chapter 8 will show how improved versions as well.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:06.000
 In the meantime, however, many applications really only need a trivial Alec to dispense little pieces of storage of unpredictable sizes at unpredictable times.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:14.000
 The simplest implementation is to have Alec hand out pieces of a large character array, which we will call Alec buff.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:20.000
 This array is private to Alec and free since they deal in pointers and not array indices.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:30.000
 No other routine need know the name of the array, which can be declared as external static that is local to the source file containing Alec and free and invisible outside it.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:36.000
 In practical implementations, the array may well not even have a name.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:42.000
 It might be obtained by asking the operating system for a pointer to some unnamed block of storage.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:46.000
 The other information needed is how much Alec buff has been used.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:50.000
 We use a pointer to the next free element called Alec CP.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:57.000
 When Alec is asked for n characters, it checks to see if there is enough room left in Alec buff.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:07.000
 If so, Alec returns the current value of Alec P, i.e. the beginning of the free block, and then increments it by n to point to the next free area.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:14.000
 Free P merely sets Alec P to P if P is inside Alec buff.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:18.000
 This next code example is on page 97 of the textbook.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:25.000
 You can see the code at www.cc4e.com/code.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:33.000
 #include sddio.h #define null 0 (it's a pointer value for in the error report)

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:38.000
 #define alec_size 1000 (the size of the available space)

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:44.000
 static char alec_buff open square bracket alec_size close square bracket semicolon

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:54.000
 static char char star alec_p = alec_buff next free position initialized to the start of the array

00:25:54.000 --> 00:26:05.000
 char star alec open paren n close paren return a pointer to n characters int n semicolon open curly brace

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:17.000
 if alec_cp + n less than or equal to alec_buff + alec_size close paren open curly brace (meaning we have space)

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:26.000
 alec_cp + = n return alec_cp - n close parenthesis semicolon close curly brace

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:34.000
 else if there's not enough room return open paren null close paren semicolon close curly brace

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:40.000
 free open paren p close paren (this function will free the storage 22 by p)

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:51.000
 char star p open curly brace if p greater than or equal to alec_buff and p less than alec_buff + alec_size

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:56.000
 alec_cp = p close curly brace

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:58.000
 some explanations

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:06.000
 In general, a pointer can be initialized just as any other variable can, though normally only meaningful values are null (discussed below)

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:11.000
 or an expression involving the address of a previously defined data of the appropriate type.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:24.000
 The declaration "static char star alec_cp = alec_buff" defines alec_cp to be a character pointer and initializes it to point to alec_buff,

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:28.000
 which is the next free position when the program starts.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:37.000
 This could also have been written "static char star alec_cp = ampersand alec_buff sub 0 semicolon"

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:44.000
 since the array name is the address of the zeroth element, whichever is more natural.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:57.000
 The test if open paren alec_p + n less than or equal to alec_buff + alec_size checks if there's enough room to satisfy a request for n characters.

00:27:57.000 --> 00:28:04.000
 If there is, the new value of alec_p would be at most 1 beyond the end of alec_buff.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:11.000
 If the request can be satisfied, alec returns a normal pointer (notice the declaration of the function itself).

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:16.000
 If not, alec must return some kind of signal that there's no space left.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:21.000
 C guarantees that no pointer that validly points to data will ever contain a 0,

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:29.000
 so a return value of 0 can be used to signal an abnormal event, in this case no space.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:36.000
 We write null instead of 0, however to indicate more clearly that this is a special value for a pointer.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:43.000
 In general, integers cannot be meaningfully assigned to pointers, but 0 is a special case.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:29:02.000
 Tests like if open paren alec_p + n less than or equal to alec_buff + alec_size and if open paren p greater than or equal to alec_buff and p less than alec_buff + alec_size show several important facets of pointer arithmetic.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:16.000
 First, pointers may be compared on certain circumstances. If p and q point to members of the same array, then relations like less than, greater than, equal, etc. work properly.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:24.000
 p greater than q is true, for example, if p points to an earlier member of the array than q.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:36.000
 The relations double equals and not equals exclamation equals also work. Any pointer can be meaningfully compared for equality or inequality with null.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:54.000
 But all bets are off if you do arithmetic or comparisons with pointers that point to different arrays. If you're lucky, you get obvious nonsense on all machines. If you're unlucky, your code will work on one machine but collapse mysteriously on another.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:30:07.000
 Second, we've already observed that a pointer and an integer can be added or subtracted. The construction p + n means the nth object beyond the one p currently points to.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:20.000
 This is true regardless of the kind of object p is declared to point at. The compiler scales n according to the size of the objects p points to, which is determined by the declaration of p.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:34.000
 For example, on the PDP-11, the factors are 1 for char, 2 for int, and short, and 4 for long float and float, and 8 for double. Pointer subtraction is also valid.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:48.000
 If p and q point to members of the same array, p-q is the number of elements between p and q. This fact can be used to write yet another version of Stirlen.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:31:09.000
 Stirlen open paren s close paren char star s semicolon open curly brace char star p equals s semicolon while star p not equal backslash single quote backslash zero single quote close paren p++ semicolon.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:16.000
 Return open paren p-s close paren semicolon close curly brace.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:28.000
 In its declaration, p is initialized s, that is to point to the first character. In the while loop, each character in turn is examined until backslash zero at the end is seen.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:45.000
 Since backslash zero is zero and since while tests only whether the expression is zero, it is possible to omit the explicit test, and such loops are often written as while open paren star p close paren p++ semicolon.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:58.000
 Because p points to characters, p++ advances p up to the next character each time, and p-s gives the number of characters advanced over, that is the string length.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:09.000
 Pointer arithmetic is consistent. If we'd been dealing with floats, which occupy more storage than chars, and if p were a pointer to a float, p++ would advance to the next float.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:18.000
 Thus, we could write another version of alloc, which maintains, say, floats instead of chars, merely by changing char to float throughout alloc and free.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:27.000
 All the pointer manipulations automatically take into the account the size of the object pointed to, so nothing else has to be altered.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:37.000
 Other than the operations mentioned here, adding or subtracting a pointer in an integer, subtracting or comparing two pointers, all other pointer arithmetic is illegal.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:47.000
 It is not permitted to add two pointers, or to multiply, or divide, or shift, or mass them, or add float or double to them.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:52.000
