 Section 5.10, pointers versus multi-dimensional arrays.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:21.000
 Newcomers to C are sometimes confused about the difference between a two-dimensional array and an array of pointers, such as name in the example above.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:36.000
 Given the declarations int, a, open square bracket, 10, closed square bracket, open square bracket, 10, closed square bracket, semicolon, and int star b, open square bracket, 10, closed square bracket, semicolon,

01:07:36.000 --> 01:07:46.000
 the usage of a and b may be similar in that a sub 5, 5 and b sub 5, 5 are both legal references to a single integer.

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:56.000
 But a is a true array. All 100 storage cells have been allocated, and the conventional rectangular substrip calculation is done to find any given element.

01:07:56.000 --> 01:08:04.000
 For b, however, the declaration only allocates 10 pointers. Each must be set to point to an array of integers.

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:14.000
 Assuming that each does point to a 10-element array, then there will be 100 storage cells set aside, plus the 10 cells for the pointers.

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:21.000
 Thus, the array of pointers uses slightly more space and may require an explicit initialization step.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:32.000
 But it has two advantages. Accessing an element is done by indirection through a pointer rather than by a multiplication and an addition, and the rows of the array may be of different lengths.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:42.000
 That is, each element of b need not point to a 10-element vector. Some may point to two elements, others may point to 20, and some to none at all.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:53.000
 Although we have phrased this discussion in terms of integers, by far the most frequent use of arrays of pointers is like that shown in monthname, to store character strings of a diverse length.

01:08:53.000 --> 01:09:06.000
 Section 5.11, command line arguments. In environments that support c, there is a way to pass command line arguments or parameters to a program when it begins executing.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:17.000
 When main is called to begin execution, it is called with two arguments. The first, conventionally called argc, is the number of command line arguments the program was invoked with.

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:24.000
 The second, argv, is a pointer to an array of character strings that contain the arguments, one per string.

01:09:24.000 --> 01:09:30.000
 Manipulating these character strings is a common use of multiple levels of pointers.

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:41.000
